A Americana-style crony capitalism
Do you remember the Asian financial crisis? When the American Treasury and its IMF allies shifted the blame for this region's problems onto crony capitalism, lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
The countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
Regardless of whether under the guidance of its own entrepreneurs, Asia has developed faster than any other region - and with greater stability - over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "A house divided against itself cannot stand."
Enron used complex accounting maneuvers and sophisticated financial derivatives to mislead investors about its true value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to acquire influence and power, shape US energy policy, and evade regulations.
Crony capitalism is not new, nor is it the domain of one party.
The former American Secretary of the Treasury, Robert Rubin, tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards board attempted to clean up the accounts of top executives' perks.
It was partly thanks to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was impeded.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is merely a thin veneer for the well-being of old companies: giving favors to those with good connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed speaks to the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: this speaks to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to investigate Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Campaign contributions were not simply in the public interest, but constituted an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, it worked out well in the short term but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some relate to politics: the Enron scandal reinforces the arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are eroded by corporate interests that in fact buy elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to the economy, particularly to information economics.
For the markets to function properly and to provide the appropriate signals aimed at efficiently allocating resources, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present the rosiest possible picture.
The control of accounts is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guards?
Who will control the account controllers?
We rely heavily on motivations.
The auditors wish to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between consulting and accounting control practices brings in other corrupted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former president of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unknown hero of the debacle.
But the accounting firms and their corporate clients – given the conspiracy that has developed – fiercely attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood - and what the Enron debacle so clearly showed - is that motivations matter, but that unhampered markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
Markets cannot provide motivations for creating wealth; they can provide motivations for the types of schemes Enron implemented.
The new economy - and its new complex financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to manipulate.
Rather than facing the problems, corporate America systematically turns away from them, supported and encouraged by American favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time consists in finding the right balance between government and market.
The status quo will assert that Enron was an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will.
But the vast majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors declare that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act similarly.
They are right - and that is indeed the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received reflects the economic situation of a company sufficiently.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no means of being offered these guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Though we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we see that they manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes apparent, new venues for abuse are created time and again - take the repeal of the Glass Steagall Act in the United States, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly witnessed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to lean towards the other extreme.
The challenge lies in achieving the right balance.
